The first book of the Metamorphoses opens with an account of the Creation, ll. 1-88. To this succeeds the Four Ages, 11. 89—162. The wickedness of mankind gives occasion for the tale of the wicked king of Arcadia, Lycaon, ll. 163—252. Next comes the Flood, ll. 253—312‚ with its sequeI, the stom* of Deucalion and Pyrrha, ll. 313—415.
